<br>
I don't know if we'll ever see a big ground launched ship. It might be nice to see a few of these lift off with a million ton+ cargo. It really could vastly speed up our movement into space.<br>
OTOH, we do know about bootstrapping, and we do know about HLVs and maybe by-passing the present monopoly on space travel by the military/industrialists. (And bootstrapping is very useful even if you do get a million tons into space in one shot for a few cents.)<br>
 I like the 10 meter design, lifted into HEO by (currently easily built) chemical HLVs, as a perfectly feasible way to plant &quot;seed&quot; space factories at NEAs. That is easily done today and would vastly facilitate our reach into space.<br>
<br>
For anybody who says safe routine space travel is beyond us, and that space travel must always remain dangerous and for the daring few super-human astronauts, I point at these &quot;super&quot; orion ships. Whether or not they can be launched from Earth, they are entirely feasible if used in space, and they revolutionize our conception of what space travel might be like.<br>
<br>
Millions of tons structure, millions of tons habitation, millions of tons cargo, <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">and</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> incredibly rapid interplanetary trajectories (I don't <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>care</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> about interstellar travel!), all with readily understood technology!<br>
